text: I don't think people appreciate how unique the way he went about making these films were. Sure you can compare it to something like the Nolan Batman movies and say it comes full circle with a complete story but it tells multiple ones with different characters throughout different films. Much like that of an actual comic where characters show up and stories bridge over from different issues but this doesn't feel like a giant interconnected universe like the MCU. It's self contained but expansive and that's what makes it interesting.

text: If this is a cinematic universe, the battle between the three guys here should spill into the Village, revealing the truth to it's inhabitants. Mel Gibson is institutionalized because he claims he fought demons(If you guys had paid attention while watching Signs, you'd know that they are demons, not aliens). Walberg is also curious about Dun, Glass and Kevin and wonder if their abilities are connected to the plants, we also learn that the Lady in the Water also a connection to wherever all these powers are coming from. We also learn that the institution the 3 guys are kept at is where Nana and Pop Pop were held before they escaped.   In a later movie, a new heroine called Korra enters the frey who ponders if what has been happening to all the others guys, is what's allowing her to manipulate the 4 elements. She later recieves vision from a mysterious being of Light called Raava, as well as two other strange fish like beings who claim to be the moon and ocean. All three of the tell her to seek out the other heroes. The mysterious force that is causing all this crazy stuff to happen is also causing animals to become wilder and more ferocious, and if that's not enough, Osmond ponders why Dun looks like a ghost teacher he had as a child. Also, for the cherry on the top, all the heroes come face to face with a strange guy who seems to always pop up all the time. One time he appeared as Osmond's doctor, he later was Gibson's neighbor, later as a security guard at a national park, and most recently he was the landlord of Macavoy's psychiatrist. Turns out he's some sort of magic advisor who will sometimes appear to give advice, wisdom or help people out with their problems. If all the heroes then unite to stop a new yet to be revealed villain, the strange guy then says "My work is done." and vanishes.

These three people don't really have super powers, but their belief that they do is what makes it real. This is a very profound concept, one of Mind over Matter. The only flaw with this theory is that in Unbreakable David(Bruce Willis) never realized he was invincible until after Mr. Glass found him and planted the seed of thought into his mind. But I'm sure this could be corrected with a few lines of dialogue. Regardless, I'm very excited to see what M. text: I met a girl when I lived in China. She spoke pretty good English, attractive, dressed well and came from a pretty good family. She was later 20s or so. Anyone could see there was something completely off about her in the first minute of talking to her. She wrote me a long note in pinyin and I had a friend help me translate it to English. When I read it I was shocked. The story she told was about extraterrestrials and other planets and how SHE ALONE knew how to save the world. I studied psych in college and she was textbook loony, with delusions of grandeur. I thought it was cool that I met someone like that, because most psychopathologies are not that clearly evident. Was gratifying that my minor in psych finally came in handy.
This trailer made me have to go watch split.  Now i am super pumped for this movie.

If you don't read you WILL be abducted by grey aliens tonight üëΩ (no pressure) When life gets rough there's always that one thing we as humans can go back to and feel like everything is alright. In my opinion that thing is good music. There have been so many days before when I was younger where everything seemed so overwhelmingly negative... Like there was no light at the end of my tunnel. But then I started listening to my idols, marshmello and zedd included, and somehow it made me feel some sort of way... Almost like a hope entered into my life. At that moment I knew what my dream in life was.   I wanted to make music like my favorite artists. I knew I'd never be able to even afford a keyboard so it stayed a dream, buried deep inside me never to see the light of day. Until now that is. Here I am  few years later and I'm making the music I'd always look for but never could find. This journey in my life has been amazing... And I want to help people feel the same way by listening to the music I create... I wanna be able to make memories for other people. I want people to hear my music and let it change your day for the better! That's why I started making music. üååThey're not your typical dance tracks. My songs are flooded with emotion and vibes. text: Keep an eye on who you think the protagonist is. I don't think it's necessarily going to be Dunn vs. Price and Crumb. Dr. Staple may serve as a primary protagonist or antagonist in this - she represents the world who does not accept the idea of supernatural heroes, an idea which Elijah is committed to spreading across the world. In this regard, Dunn is her enemy just as much as the other two. Is the true conflict of the movie going to be Elijah pushing comic tropes upon the world? Remember, Dunn defeated that in Unbreakable - he could have had a 'superhero confrontation' with Glass at the end but instead did the right thing and turned him in to the authorities in an anti-climactic fashion.

text: Wow, what an epic trailer. Unbreakable is such an underrated movie. Seeing these 3 characters together makes me so excited. They are all really well developed and complex characters. If you were tired of super hero movies this will surely pull you back in because it's so different, realistic and grounded. Realistic as in; it's not that people can fly or have extreme "superhero" abilities, but more mysteriously, incomprehensible and unexplained powers that just make it more interesting. It's about how these characters interact with each other and the real world. No red capes or million dollar Iron Man expenses. Just a simple raincoat, a wheelchair and a distorted multiple personality disorder. Go watch this movie. But before you do, watch Unbreakable (2000) first, then (Split 2016). You will not be disapointed. Buy a ticket and go see this movie. *Thumbs up* and thanks for reading.

text: Certainly promising but we have to remain skeptical knowing Shyamalan's track record.  In recent years he's been at his worst when he's taken his material too seriously allowing for his writing to descend into some really poor, shockingly illogical and self-serious writing.  Split was a perfect blend of tension and bizarre levity but it knew where to draw the line and came close to jumping over it toward the end but luckily held itself together for the most part.  It'll be interesting to see how he handles the tones between Unbreakable and Split here.

text: It is finally here. The age of post-superhero films. Unbreakable was released in 2000. An incredible film and 20 years before its time. But now we have reached peak superhero cinema where the the masses are teetering on the edge of superhero fatigue and are finally ready. Ready to think more deeply about what superheroes represent as an idea- as a concept- and what they can teach us about ourselves in a profound (and super rad) way.  "Unbreakable" was truly great. "Split" wet our palate and hopefully- hopefully "Glass" will live up to the promise. Bring on the intellectually mature superhero film!

text: Analysis here: The three colors on the poster correspond the the chakras each character harnesses their strengths from. Purple is mind aka crown, yellow is willpower aka solar plexus. Green is heart.   They sit in this order to show their relationship with one another. Horde is exhibiting an innocent alter and is not chained; however, David is chained and Glass is "chained" via disability. Put this into perspective, the most dangerous person is smiling, unchained. Both Mr Glass and David disagree on how far to go but both have good intentions through vigilante ways.  It's a good chance Mr Glass and Bruce will work together. They're in psych ward because the only person whose powers are based on belief ie willpower is horde.  The psychologist got Horde to believe he was special rather than discovering it like Glass and David. Without belief Horde is nothing.

text: My theory for the inevitability twist: Mr. Glass has The Horde holding innocent folk hostage, demanding that David Dunn now prove to the world (just as it was proven to Price years ago) that heroes exist or have the deaths of these folks on his head. David fights The Horde anyways, and it looks like Glass will end up killing the innocents himself....  .... suddenly, a shadow shrouded figure appears, breaking Glass and free the hostages, seemingly able to stay one step ahead of The Horde by ducking into shadows, being where the villain isn‚Äôt seeing, and striking when he is vulnerable. David shows back up and fully defeats Horde. David then thanks the other guy for helping but tells him he shouldn‚Äôt have come alone. The figure says ‚ÄúI‚Äôm never alone‚Äù... panning back to the other figure, we see the slain folks of The Horde (including the psychologist and the girls who were eaten in Split) disappearing into the shadows around the figure, who is revealed to be Cole Sear from the Sixth Sense (once again played by Haley Joel Osment), who was there to help the ghosts killed by The Horde get their closure (who in turn helped him in the fight by being ghostly eyes and ears to help him evade and attack The Horde).

text: Unbreakable and Split are very different from each other but also kinda similar.   Unbreakable is a slowly paced drama with a satisfying payoff. It's a very interesting take on the superhero genre that I enjoyed greatly. Split is a faster paced horror/thriller that is more intense and satisfying to most audiences. I like both of them very much.  If you haven't seen Unbreakable yet you're not alone, but just know it's not as "have a good time with your friends" friendly as Split. That being said I would still recommend it to all of you.

A more street level, an everyman kind of supers genre.  I like the Marvel movies, and while I also like DC, they cant seem to decide what they are doing. DC is either overly gritty and then chopped to make it more Marvel. Or, now with SHAZAM! its trying to go, well...I'll just say I wont be watching it. No matter what, the future of the superhero genre looks promising. (Still hoping they could do something interesting with Chronicle though)

text: Prediction: Casey from Split will emerge with mind control/suggestive powers.   1. The broken are the more evolved. She is confirmed as broken, which points to her being a candidate to be more evolved.  2. She somehow had the attention of all the personalities, and could seemingly always get them to cater to her and even admire her. Almost as if the Horde sensed something different about her. Think about it, every personality treated her differently than the other girls, Patricia and Hedwig in particular, and the simple fact the Beast chose not to kill her was an obvious clue that there was something more to her.  3. She told the girl to pee, and the girl did. Now, this sounds like suggestive reasoning, and maybe it is, but is it possible that she implanted that into the girls mind, notice how she grabs her head......which I'll speak further on later.  4. Now this is stretching a bit, but did you notice that when Kevin first gets in the car with the girls, that he seemingly didn't even notice Casey was right there next to him? Almost as if she had somehow concealed his mind from seeing her when she got scared, until her concentration broke when she opened the door and all the sudden he saw her...notice in particular how he looks at her as if he was surprised. The Dennis personality is OCD and extremely detailed in his approach. how did he not notice her right away or make a point to go after her right away being she was the closest?   5. At the end with the cop, the look she gave the cop that signaled the cop to something being wrong. Now...pay special attention to the cops face, it‚Äôs not just the cop getting something is wrong. It‚Äôs an almost shocked look as if the cop can see what she‚Äôs thinking and reacting to it.  Now back to the grabbing the girls head part, watch this trailer and see how she once again grabs Kevin by the head and how he reacts, he looks shocked, or stunned even. Which indicates she may be exhibiting her mind control ability.  COMMON THEMES BETWEEN UNBREAKABLE AND SPLIT:  ¬†Glass is weak and genius and malevolent and the opposite to David Dunn‚Äôs durability and simple focus, and benevolence.   Kevin is split and unable to control even his own mind and primal, while Casey is whole and able to control other minds and nurturing.  Also keep in mind, Mr. Glass in fact 'awakened' David Dunn to what he could really do and what he really was, by finding his opposite on the spectrum. The 'broken are the more evolved' line, I believe, is the moment when Casey was also awakened to being more evolved. Regardless of whether she initially realized it or not or even knew what that meant. Continuing the theme of the awakened heroes via the villains.......

text: DON'T LISTEN TO THE CRITICS! M. Night has done it again! I was at the edge of my seat trying to figure out how this will end and then when it does my jaw drops, which is is a common recurring thing that happens when I watch M. Night's movies and that is very well a GOOD thing, which means he is doing something right! This movie is not like any other superhero movie I have seen. M. Night brings such a realistic bend. From the fight scenes, which are played out like it truly would be in real life, the conflict through the characters of battling the belief in real super powers, to the whole demeanor of the movie, it has such a realistic and literal vibe to the plot that sets it apart from all the other superhero movies and making the audience truly believe that the concept of superpowers could actually be real. Its stunningly executed from the cinematography, score, color scheme, plot and all of the above. Not to Mention James McAvoy's acting was presented stunningly. I didn't think his acting could get any better after Split, but it did! WHY HASN'T THIS GUY WON AN OSCAR YET!?!? If your looking for a remarkable superhero movie like no other, I wouldn't recommend any other movie than this one!

Let's be honest, it can be way way way more amazing if Shyamalan combine the cinematography of "Unbreakable" and the script of "Split", yet we see little to none of these great points in the movie. Acting is....well...acceptable i guess. The only ones believable in this movie are the "Split" casts as they were in a great movie before and also they are good actors/actresses ( James Mcavoy is pretty much carrying the whole sequel). Samuel's death is kinda off since i expect for a brainer psychopath he could have been out-smart everyone till the end, but i guess that's what you need to end a trilogy.   Tl, DR: it's another Micheal Bay's Transformer sequel. Fun to watch, fun to see old characters meet up, but don't really care about plot.

text: This is how the theatre reacted to this movie.... So about the first half of the movie, I could hear people weren't into it. I heard talking. People mostly wondering what's going on. A lot of confusing stuff that didn't make sense. THEN. The last 40 percent of the movie. The "break out" scenes. The audience was dead silent. Glued to it. In awe. Not a peep from anyone. Until the last scene. And when the credits rolled...Nobody got up. It was weird. Usually ppl start leaving when the ending music plays. Or, the first word of the credit appears. But not this film....people wanted more. I've never seen an entire theatre watch the whole credits. We all wanted a bonus scene. Or maybe, it was so good at the end, we were paralyzed. Well done M Night Shamalan!  VERY nice comeback :)

text: I absolutely love Shyamalan's approach to villains in this trilogy. In Unbreakable, Mr. Glass' arc was about him proving to himself that superheroes and villains were real and that he was a part of that world. He was finally able to let go of his lifelong existential crisis. During the years between that film and Glass, however, he once again sank into a depression because he gradually realized that finding David wasn't enough to truly change things.   Then, miraculously, fate brought The Overseer and The Horde to the very institution he was imprisoned in, and a new purpose for himself emerged. If the world could witness a battle between those two invulnerable, super-strong titans, they would be awakened to the potential within themselves, just as he was while reading comic books but to a much further and more powerful extent. What he did for himself in Unbreakable, he would now do for others. If Unbreakable ended with him being the villain, Glass ends with him being an anti-hero. And believe it or not, this is all foreshadowed very subtly in the scene in Unbreakable where a young Elijah Price receives his very first comic book.

He changed into them so quickly and so often, it became uninteresting. We get it, James, you're great at accents **eyeroll** :p  3) I felt the last moment of Split, he shouldnt have changed lights so much. It shouldve been Dennis the protector, then Hedgewig the cheated child, then finally Kevin so he die in mental peace. Because in truth, that was all he was. A damaged child who developed personalities to protect himself.  4) M Knight Shaylaman ruined this movie by mocking superhero films. WHY did he do this? He shouldve continued with the mystery of "are they superhuman?" instead of then having Glass narrate/predict "the showdown" and everything else. This is the first time I have ever witnessed a movie spoiler WITHIN the movie.  What once was interesting and had potential turned out to be extremely jaded and disappointing. Did the actors agree to the film but only on conditions of "Let me die, cuz I'm not into doing another sequel"??? I thought the movie Split was so interesting because it created wonder about disabilities, the supernatural, mental illness and intelligence. And now this movie just totally crumpled the hypothesis. Just...bruh.....  5) Again, Glass shows up mid-film and his origins are just...."lemme squeeze this character right here so I can make the twist of all twists'' but theres really not much more about him. Maybe I just need to see the film again? I'm up for it. I could use a second look. What did you all think?

text: Why, are so many critics taking their perceived high road and shitting on this film for portraying dissociative identity disorder for horror and laughs? It seems hypocritical for critics to be up in arms about this when past and present filmmakers, in Hollywood, and around the world, have been making movies with psychotic antagonists for a century or more. text: It's disheartening to see so many reviews of the movie never once acknowledges how the entire movie follows the tropes and sequences of comic books in general. For the love of god, read white knight, civil war, m-day, and other comics series and tell me they dont follow the same flow. This is a love letter to comics and all of them berates the movie for having so many twists when there was only ever one. Everything else had already been foreshadowed by split and unbreakable i cannot understand how and why people thought they were twists. It's almost as if they came to the theatres expecting to see an avengers showdown instead of the confrontation between the main characters and their alienation--the very question glass posed at the start of the movie, in unbreakable and split.

In a movie where you're not quite sure if there is anything mythical going on, you're not quite sure if they really are super villains, or super heroes, or that they even have any power... then you catch just a glimpse of it, and thats all we needed. We dont need the earth blowing up, and some massive universe scale epic battle montage, with gods among men, and super weapons that destroy worlds.... we just needed a taste of that comic book flair.

text: On a rare, lazy afternoon off, I decided to go ahead and rent "Glass" via YouTube on a whim, having wanted to watch it after watching the trailers online. I was pleasantly surprised, and glad that I did so. I honestly think that this may be Shyamalan's best film; perhaps topped only by "Unbreakable" and "The Sixth Sense."  Certainly, it brings him a considerable artistic redemption, after over a decade of duds and disappointing, cheap "twist" endings. (I was a big Shyamalan fan...and then he lost me with the "surprise" he threw in at the end of "The Village." Even "Signs", considered one of his great early works, concludes by tying everything together in a rather pat and incoherent manner.)  Here, though, the twist ending (which I won't spoil!) is *real*; it is genuinely surprising, thought-provoking, and fully supported by everything else which has led up to it, not only in "Glass" itself, but in its predecessors, "Unbreakable" and "Split." The concluding message, and they way it is conveyed through the musical score, characters' reactions and expressions, and final unfolding of events, is legitimately moving, potentially even inspiring, if you choose to reflect on it, and apply it to real life and our existing world off-screen.  Well done, Mr. Shyamalan. (And actors Taylor-Joy, Paulson, Woodard, Jackson, McAvoy, Clark, and Willis; and everyone else who worked on this film, as cast or crew.) Well done, indeed.
